on the surface of CNT introduced by strong acid oxidation could
provide covalent-bonding interfacial interaction between the titanate
sol and CNTs
. However, the acid oxidation treatments also inev-
itably shorten the CNT and destroy the structure of CNT which
degrade its electronic conductivity and mechanical strength.
Recently, Eder
et al.
reported a non-covalent process to enable
coating of TiO
on the CNTs by using benzyl alcohol (BA) as the
surfactant. The phenyl ring of the BA attached to the graphitic sur-
face of CNTs
via
p
p
stacking, and then the hydroxyl group of the
BA interacted directly with the precursors in the sol-gel process as
linkers
. Hence, BA enables the synthesis of CNT-inorganic hybrid
materials without the requirement of covalent functionalization of
CNT. However, the uses of extra additives undoubtedly increase the
synthesis complexity, the cost, and pose potential hazards to the
environment. Therefore, it is highly desirable but quite challenging
to design a simple and green route to integrate TiO
with highly
conductive CNTs at nanoscale for using as high-performance anode
material.
In this work, we present a simple and green one-pot route to form
a new nanostructured CNT@TiO
-C nanocable by using glucose as
structure-directing agent and carbon source without any prerequisite
for covalent/non-covalent functionalization of CNTs. Although glu-
cose is often used as a carbon source in hydrothermal reactions
, it
is the first time to be used as a structure-directing agent to form
CNT@TiO
-C nanocable. It was reported that some aromatic com-
pounds can be produced during the hydrothermal process of
glucose
. Therefore, it can be expected that these aromatic com-
pounds with multiple hydroxyl groups originated from glucose can
act as a bridge to connect TiO
and CNTs by
p
p
interactions just
like the BA surfactant
. Consistent with the hypothesis, using the
glucose as structure-directing agent and carbon source, a newhybrid
nanostructure CNT@TiO
-C nanocable with high electronic and
ionic conducting network was prepared in one pot, which showed
high specific capacity, superior rate capability, and excellent long-
termcycling stability as anode material for LIBs in half cell. Figure 1
shows the one-pot hydrothermal routine to prepare the CNT@TiO
C nanocable. Using glucose to facilitate the formation of CNT@
TiO
-C nanocable in one pot presents multiple highlights: 1) the
utilization of glucose not only solves the interfacial incompatibility
between CNTs and titanate sol, but also provides molecular template
to control the nucleation and growth of TiO
; 2) the carbon-rich
polysaccharide derived from the glucose can integrate the TiO
nanoparticles with high electronic conductive CNT core to form a
three-dimensional electronic conducting network; 3) the whole pro-
cess is simple and intrinsically green because it only uses CNTs,
titanium isopropoxide, and glucose as the precursors (see Experi-
mental Section for more details); 4) glucose is an abundant and
environmentally benign product, which can reduce the cost of the
hybrid material.
Results
The morphology of the prepared CNT@TiO
-C hybrid material was
characterized by scanning electron microscopy (SEM), high resolu-
tion transmission electron microscopy (HR-TEM), and Z-contrast
annular dark-field scanning transmission electron microscopy
(ADF-STEM). Compared with pristine CNTs shown in Fig. 2a, the
CNT@TiO
-C nanocables preserve the one-dimensional nanostruc-
ture of the CNT with the diameters ranging from 20 to 30 nm
(Fig. 2b–c). The surfaces of CNTs become coarse, indicating the
coating of TiO
and carbon. The transmission electron microscopy
(TEM) images in Fig. 2d show that a thin carbon layer was continu-
ously wrapped on the TiO
nanoparticles. The presence of the carbon
layer resulted fromthe carbonization of glucose derivatives can effec-
tively improve the electronic conductivity of the hybrid material.
Meanwhile, the carbon layer can act as a separator to restrain the
growth of primary TiO
nanoparticles during the hydrothermal and
annealing process and therefore keep the particle size at nanoscale.
The crystallite sizes are below 8 nm as determined from TEM
images. The lattice fringes observed in HR-TEM image (Fig. 2e)
and its corresponding fast Fourier transform (FFT) pattern in
Fig. 2f reveal the crystal structure to be anatase TiO
. From ADF-
STEMZ-contrast images (Fig. 2g), it is shown that the high-contrast
TiO
nanoparticles covering on the surface of CNT are relatively
homogeneous. The near-edge fine structure of the Ti L2,3 edge in
the electron energy loss spectrum designates the nanoparticles to be
stoichiometric TiO
. To better illustrate the nanostructure of the
CNT@TiO
-C, more SEM and TEM images at different magnifica-
tions are provided in supplementary Fig. S1 and Fig. S2. Nitrogen
isothermal adsorption-desorption measurements were performed to
determine the Brunauer-Emmett-Teller (BET) surface area and the
porosity of the prepared material. Supplementary Fig. S3 shows the
adsorption/desorption isotherms of CNT@TiO
-C nanocables,
which exhibits a hysteresis of typical type IV isotherm, demonstrat-
ing a porous structure with a BETspecific surface area of 75.8 m
g
The XRD pattern of the CNT@TiO
-C nanocable is shown in
Fig. 3a. The diffraction pattern is in good agreement with anatase
TiO
(JCPDS 21-1272). Raman spectra were carried out to invest-
igate the crystalline phase of TiO
and the carbon type in the nanoc-
able (Fig. 3b). Four peaks with strong intensities at 146, 395, 515, and
635 cm
can be observed in the Raman spectra of the CNT@TiO
-C
nanocable, which are well consistent with that of reported anatase
TiO
. Furthermore, two characteristic peaks located at about 1372
and 1592 cm
correspond to disorder carbon (D-band) and graph-
ite carbon (G-band) in the nanocable, respectively. The peak intens-
ity ratio of D-band and G-band (I
D
/I
G
) is found to be 1.5 for CNT@
TiO
-C nanocable compared with the I
D
/I
G
value of pristine CNTs
(about 1.0), which clearly demonstrates the existence of amorphous
carbon in CNT@TiO
-Cnanocable. The total carbon content includ-
ing carbon nanotube and amorphous carbon is directly obtained
from the TGA (see supplementary Fig. S4 online).
To unravel the impact of the glucose and CNTs on the structure
formation, the samples were prepared in the absence of glucose and
CNTs. In sharp contrast, in the absence of the glucose, TiO
preci-
pitated in form of large clusters (named as CNT/TiO
composite)
without the formation of the nanocable (Fig. 4a–b). Without the
addition of CNT and glucose, only agglomerated TiO
nanoparticles
were obtained (Fig. 4c–d). Eder
